Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it without opening a real port.

**Key pattern:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using Xunit;

public class McpIntegrationTests
    : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                clientInfo = new { name = "test", version = "1.0" },
                capabilities = new { }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.GetProperty("result")
                .GetProperty("protocolVersion")
                .GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsList_ReturnsRegisteredTools()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/list",
            @params = new { }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var tools = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("tools");
        Assert.True(tools.GetArrayLength() > 0);
    }
}
```

**Why this works well:**

| Concern | How it's handled |
|---|---|
| No real port | `WebApplicationFactory` uses an in-memory test server |
| Full middleware pipeline | Routing, auth, DI — all run exactly as in production |
| MCP protocol fidelity | You send real JSON-RPC 2.0 payloads over HTTP |
| Service overrides | Call `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` to swap dependencies |

**Tips:**

- If your MCP endpoint uses **SSE** (Streamable HTTP), read the response stream with `ReadAsStreamAsync()` and parse `text/event-stream` lines.
- Override services (e.g., stub a database) via `WithWebHostBuilder`:
  ```csharp
  factory.WithWebHostBuilder(builder =>
      builder.ConfigureServices(services =>
          services.AddSingleton<IMyService, FakeMyService>()));
  ```
- Make sure `Program` is accessible to your test project (add `InternalsVisibleTo` or a `public partial class Program { }` marker).
